See when it was only the top 2-3 guilds doing it its easy to make a gentlemans agreement because they both made out, now that more guilds are doing it, they have to once again change the rules to suit them best.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Oh, hey, here's a newsflash... this 'change' is the written convention of the gentleman's agreement. That means that *shock* there was no change, except to tell people about it in a public way. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
If you want compliance, present it and deal with it properly, dont just make some last minute changes to cover your own asses to try and show that you are right.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Present it to who exactly? You? Me? <br>
<br>
Why? So we can bicker about the Dozekar rotation, a rotation that we havn't earned a place on yet? <br>
<br>
Yeah, that sounds fair. Oh wait, no it doesn't. <br>
<br>
The bottom line is fairly easy: The rotations are conventions. If you feel so strongly that they are evil and wrong, you are not bound by any rule of the game in an enforceable way to follow them. No one will stop you in any way from taking any and all the named drakes if that is your desire. You can at will, ignore any and all rotations on this server.<br>
<br>
The fact that people usually don't violate those conventions suggests to me that the people who feel they are horrible and wrong and unjust number in a minority so small, that they do not even have the numbers requisite to form a guild strong enough to actually kill one of the rotation mobs. <br>
<br>
That suits me just fine. Let the misfits go FFA on the frenzied ghoul while guilds of at least semi-mature people work within the community to advance and attempt new things. <br>
<br>
Yers,<br>
